    "body": "Hey @Arachnid, @makoto \r\n\r\n> In order to be compatible with ethers and in line with other implementations, it should return the error data from eth_call as the result. \r\n\r\nYou can enable this behavior by setting `networks.hardhat.throwOnCallFailures` to `false` in your config. There's also `networks.hardhat.throwOnTransactionFailures`. When building Hardhat Network we decided to copy Ganache's non-standard behavior for compatibility reasons but added these options to let users opt-in into a more standard behavior.\r\n\r\nWould this work for you?\r\n\r\n> Alternately it could return the error data as a property on the exception that is thrown, which would be incompatible with the RPC interface of other nodes, but at least make catching and interpreting revert reasons possible.\r\n\r\nI think we should provide this info when `throwOnCallFailures` or `throwOnTransactionFailures` are enabled. This would not be standard, but unfortunately, we have already deviated from the standard. The main open question would be how to decode the arguments. We can't use ether's types inside hardhat network.",
